WEBVTT

00:00.140 --> 00:02.060
<i>Previously on "God Friended Me"... </i>

00:02.070 --> 00:04.699
We couldn't be prouder of
your nomination for bishop.

00:04.700 --> 00:06.440
During the walkabouts, you'll be meeting

00:06.460 --> 00:08.250
and answering questions
with parishioners,

00:08.260 --> 00:11.170
but there are sensitive
topics you want to

00:11.180 --> 00:12.509
pivot away from if they come up.

00:12.510 --> 00:14.439
You mean my son who is an atheist

00:14.440 --> 00:16.120
and my daughter who is gay.

00:16.140 --> 00:18.359
I did it. Five years ago,

00:18.360 --> 00:20.619
Simon Hayes goes to a New
York Presbyterian hospital

00:20.620 --> 00:22.449
for a bone marrow transplant, right?

00:22.450 --> 00:25.049
Turns out the surgeon who
did the procedure...

00:25.050 --> 00:26.660
<i>John Dove.</i>

00:26.670 --> 00:27.900
Are you okay?

00:27.930 --> 00:29.189
I think you just saved my life.

00:29.190 --> 00:30.759
How did your meeting with FreeVerse go?

00:30.760 --> 00:32.429
They want exclusivity.

00:32.430 --> 00:33.840
Well, I write about the people we help,

00:33.860 --> 00:35.100
not the God Account.

00:35.120 --> 00:36.650
That's the deal. Nothing's changed.

00:36.660 --> 00:38.150
<i>I got invited to lunch</i>

00:38.160 --> 00:39.869
<i>with the editor-in-chief at "Catapult."</i>

00:39.870 --> 00:41.709
I figured out where you
were getting your stories,

00:41.710 --> 00:43.309
but what I can't figure out

00:43.310 --> 00:46.340
is why you're not writing
who's behind the God Account.

00:46.400 --> 00:47.880
You have to kiss her. It's bad luck.

00:47.960 --> 00:51.679
<i>[WOMAN VOCALIZING]</i>

00:51.680 --> 00:55.120
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:55.180 --> 00:57.349
<i>♪ I can't be ♪</i>

00:57.350 --> 00:58.720
<i>[UPBEAT MUSIC]</i>

00:58.740 --> 01:02.289
<i>♪ Everything you want me to be ♪</i>

01:02.290 --> 01:03.959
<i>♪ I can't be ♪</i>

01:03.960 --> 01:05.829
- [LAUGHING]
- [EXHALES] What?

01:05.830 --> 01:07.829
- Looking a little winded.
- Nah. Who, me?

01:07.830 --> 01:09.669
No, no, no, no. These are...

01:09.670 --> 01:12.139
These are just deep breathes.
They're just taking in the...

01:12.140 --> 01:13.260
the fresh air.

01:14.040 --> 01:15.540
If I knew that we were
running a marathon,

01:15.550 --> 01:17.269
I would have carb-ed up
last night at dinner.

01:17.270 --> 01:19.279
About that. I had fun.

01:19.280 --> 01:21.209
Yeah, me too.

01:21.210 --> 01:22.660
I think it's safe to say
that our second date

01:22.670 --> 01:24.679
was light years ahead of our first.

01:24.680 --> 01:26.420
- [CELL PHONE CHIMES]
- Oh.

01:27.660 --> 01:29.439
Hey, it's John Dove.

01:29.440 --> 01:30.770
He said he can meet us today.

01:30.780 --> 01:31.989
- Oh, great.
- Yeah.

01:31.990 --> 01:34.259
Do you really think he can be the key

01:34.260 --> 01:36.300
to proving Simon Hayes is
behind the God Account?

01:36.320 --> 01:37.700
I mean, it's possible.

01:37.710 --> 01:39.520
Dove was my first Friend Suggestion.

01:39.530 --> 01:42.269
If he saved Simon's life,
then maybe Simon sent me

01:42.270 --> 01:44.399
his name to repay the favor.

01:44.400 --> 01:46.499
Makes sense.

01:46.500 --> 01:48.409
And if it turns out to be true,

01:48.410 --> 01:49.909
then I'll have a lot to talk about

01:49.910 --> 01:51.819
in my first podcast for FreeVerse.

01:51.820 --> 01:53.839
[LAUGHS] I'm proud of you.

01:53.840 --> 01:55.849
I know how much that
opportunity means to you.

01:55.850 --> 01:57.200
Thank you.

01:57.210 --> 01:58.880
It's all because of you.

01:58.890 --> 02:02.049
Oh, speaking of careers.

02:02.050 --> 02:03.819
I've been thinking about your lunch

02:03.820 --> 02:05.120
with your editor-in-chief.

02:05.140 --> 02:08.520
I think you should really
reconsider his offer.

02:08.560 --> 02:10.539
- You do?
- Yeah.

02:10.570 --> 02:11.680
Look, whatever he wants you to write,

02:11.700 --> 02:13.260
you're gonna make it great.

02:13.270 --> 02:14.740
You always do.

02:14.800 --> 02:17.799
<i>[SOFT MUSIC]</i>

02:17.800 --> 02:19.560
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:19.580 --> 02:21.369
Hey.

02:21.370 --> 02:22.960
You remember last time we were here?

02:23.000 --> 02:25.639
[LAUGHS] Yeah.

02:25.640 --> 02:27.100
How could I forget?

02:27.120 --> 02:29.279
It was right after we had first met.

02:29.280 --> 02:31.249
You told me to text you
if I ever heard anything

02:31.250 --> 02:32.740
back from the God Account.

02:32.750 --> 02:34.070
Hm.

02:34.080 --> 02:35.989
I'm glad you did.

02:35.990 --> 02:37.060
Although, if I'm being honest,

02:37.080 --> 02:38.220
I was gonna call you either way.

02:38.240 --> 02:39.500
Really?

02:40.900 --> 02:48.580
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:49.340 --> 02:51.539
<i>So, uh, have you heard
anything from John Dove?</i>

02:51.540 --> 02:53.239
Cara and I are gonna meet him today.

02:53.240 --> 02:54.709
Hopefully it'll lead somewhere.

02:54.710 --> 02:56.080
Hopefully?

02:56.100 --> 02:58.379
Miles, we are on the cusp

02:58.380 --> 03:00.509
of proving that Simon Hayes
is behind the God Account.

03:00.510 --> 03:02.340
- [CELL PHONE CHIMES]
- This is huge.

03:03.110 --> 03:05.180
_

03:05.200 --> 03:06.260
Hey, this is new.

03:06.270 --> 03:07.799
The God Account just rated a seller

03:07.800 --> 03:10.219
on Facebook Marketplace five stars.

03:10.220 --> 03:12.989
- Interesting.
- Karen and Richard Benson.

03:12.990 --> 03:15.059
Did the God Account actually
buy something from 'em?

03:15.060 --> 03:16.519
No, it doesn't look
like they have anything

03:16.520 --> 03:18.999
- for sale at the moment.
- Hm, 'cause technically

03:19.000 --> 03:20.799
you're not supposed to rate sellers

03:20.800 --> 03:23.129
unless you have, like, a
personal purchase history.

03:23.130 --> 03:24.760
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

03:27.220 --> 03:29.339
Mm-hmm.

03:29.340 --> 03:31.110
[DOOR OPENS]

03:33.680 --> 03:35.349
- Who was it?
- I don't know.

03:35.350 --> 03:36.899
Someone dropped off a package.

03:36.900 --> 03:40.449
It has my address, but
it's for Jen Levy.

03:40.450 --> 03:42.849
- Who's Jen Levy?
- I don't know.

03:42.850 --> 03:45.159
- Hm. Well...
- What?

03:45.160 --> 03:47.989
The God Account rates a
seller on Marketplace.

03:47.990 --> 03:50.559
Two seconds later, a package
arrives at your door.

03:50.560 --> 03:52.430
- That is not random.
- No.

03:52.460 --> 03:54.160
It's not.

03:55.760 --> 03:57.200
Look at the name of the seller.

03:57.840 --> 04:00.660
Karen and Richard Benson.

04:01.920 --> 04:04.920
- Synced & corrected by<font color="#E83286"> MementMori </font>-
-- <font color="#138CE9">www.addic7ed.com</font> --

04:04.930 --> 04:05.940
[KNOCKING]

04:06.410 --> 04:07.660
Mr. Hughes.

04:08.350 --> 04:10.409
And we're sitting. Okay.

04:10.410 --> 04:13.819
You know, Cara, I knew
from Miles podcast

04:13.820 --> 04:15.719
that Henry Chase could
be a possible suspect

04:15.720 --> 04:19.019
behind the God Account, and
then you were kind enough

04:19.019 --> 04:20.719
to tell me you had two suspects.

04:20.720 --> 04:23.089
Yes. I did.

04:23.090 --> 04:25.299
So I started doing a little digging.

04:25.300 --> 04:28.469
It turns out that Henry
Chase attended Columbia

04:28.470 --> 04:31.099
with another pioneer in the
field of predictive analytics.

04:31.100 --> 04:34.199
They even won a few awards together.

04:34.200 --> 04:35.960
Care to take a guess?

04:37.170 --> 04:39.109
Simon Hayes.

04:39.110 --> 04:41.280
- Simon Hayes.
- Mm.

04:41.850 --> 04:44.009
Now, Simon rarely gives interviews.

04:44.010 --> 04:47.379
But lucky for me, I have
some powerful friends,

04:47.380 --> 04:49.749
and I managed to score an interview

04:49.750 --> 04:53.289
with Mr. Hayes for tomorrow.

04:53.290 --> 04:56.729
<i>[COMPELLING MUSIC]</i>

04:56.730 --> 05:00.399
A journalist from "Catapult"
is taking that interview.

05:00.400 --> 05:03.720
The only question is, will it be you?

05:03.770 --> 05:05.639
[DOOR OPENS]

05:05.640 --> 05:08.659
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:08.660 --> 05:10.840
<i>For I know the plans I have for you,</i>

05:10.910 --> 05:13.659
plans to prosper you and not harm you,

05:13.660 --> 05:17.349
plans to give you hope and a future.

05:17.350 --> 05:19.119
Jeremiah 29:11.

05:19.120 --> 05:23.489
These words could not be more relevant,

05:23.490 --> 05:26.579
and that is my vision for
the Episcopalian church.

05:26.580 --> 05:28.940
And that's why I want
to be your next bishop.

05:29.690 --> 05:32.999
I know I'm new to this, but it
seems like it's going great.

05:33.000 --> 05:35.780
Like I said, he's a natural.

05:35.800 --> 05:37.600
I think we have time
for one more question.

05:38.600 --> 05:41.139
Thank you, Reverend Finer.

05:41.140 --> 05:43.550
I understand your son has a podcast

05:43.560 --> 05:45.120
where he promotes atheism.

05:46.020 --> 05:49.609
How do you expect us to
support you being bishop

05:49.610 --> 05:52.000
when you've raised a son who
doesn't believe in God?

05:52.020 --> 05:53.420
[SUCKS TEETH]

05:53.440 --> 05:55.719
Life is full of challenges.

05:55.720 --> 05:57.389
[ALL CHUCKLE]

05:57.390 --> 05:58.989
Some more difficult than others.

05:58.990 --> 06:01.040
But I do believe our true character

06:01.050 --> 06:03.359
is revealed in the face of adversity.

06:03.360 --> 06:08.329
I appreciate that, but I have to ask

06:08.330 --> 06:10.669
do you support your son's views?

06:10.670 --> 06:14.039
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

06:14.040 --> 06:17.260
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:17.310 --> 06:20.320
In this instance, I do not.

06:21.880 --> 06:25.949
But it's important for us
to hold firm in our beliefs

06:25.950 --> 06:29.819
that the common bond that
unites us will guide us

06:29.820 --> 06:32.590
through even the most difficult waters.

06:32.620 --> 06:35.259
[APPLAUSE]

06:35.260 --> 06:38.059
I think we're looking
at our next bishop.

06:38.060 --> 06:39.699
[CHUCKLES]

06:39.700 --> 06:45.099
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:45.100 --> 06:47.120
<i>The Bensons are in 2W.</i>

06:47.140 --> 06:49.669
You know, I was thinking

06:49.670 --> 06:52.579
the God Account never
does anything by mistake.

06:52.580 --> 06:55.049
So the fact that you
got Jen Levy's package

06:55.050 --> 06:56.260
maybe she has something to do with this.

06:56.270 --> 06:58.749
Yeah, it's possible, but the God Account

06:58.750 --> 07:00.240
did rate the Bensons.

07:00.250 --> 07:03.020
- Chances are, it's about them.
- Yeah.

07:09.800 --> 07:12.459
- Hi, can I help you?
- Hi. My name is Miles.

07:12.460 --> 07:14.499
- This is my friend, Rakesh.
- Hello.

07:14.500 --> 07:16.399
You wouldn't happen to be Karen Benson?

07:16.400 --> 07:17.799
- Yes.
- Oh.

07:17.800 --> 07:20.399
You sent this package to
my address by mistake.

07:20.400 --> 07:22.839
As you can see, I am not Jen Levy.

07:22.840 --> 07:26.039
Karen, who is it?

07:26.040 --> 07:27.579
What are you doing here with that?

07:27.580 --> 07:30.049
- Richard, it's a sign.
- It's not a sign, Karen.

07:30.050 --> 07:32.579
I'm sorry, we didn't want
to start any trouble.

07:32.580 --> 07:34.819
You're not.

07:34.820 --> 07:37.489
Andrea wants us to have it.
It belongs here with us.

07:37.490 --> 07:38.879
We never should have sold it.

07:38.880 --> 07:40.919
We talked about this.
We don't want it back.

07:40.920 --> 07:42.559
Now please go.

07:42.560 --> 07:44.330
Um...

07:47.650 --> 07:48.720
So what do you think is in it?

07:48.740 --> 07:50.429
I don't know.

07:50.430 --> 07:52.080
I was telling him we should just open it

07:52.090 --> 07:53.780
and find out, but he's
insisting we abide

07:53.800 --> 07:55.739
by the U.S. Postal laws.

07:55.740 --> 07:58.590
When Karen Benson saw the package,

07:58.600 --> 08:00.239
she told her husband that it was a sign

08:00.240 --> 08:01.749
that Andrea wanted her to have it.

08:01.750 --> 08:04.220
- Who's Andrea?
- I'm on it.

08:04.940 --> 08:06.619
Okay, what about Jen Levy?

08:06.620 --> 08:08.289
I mean, could she have
something to do with this?

08:08.290 --> 08:09.440
Rakesh looked into that,

08:09.450 --> 08:11.759
but there were over 50
Jen Levys in New York.

08:11.760 --> 08:14.289
Well, maybe they made
a typo on the label.

08:14.290 --> 08:15.929
Her address could be similar to yours.

08:15.930 --> 08:18.429
Yeah, we thought of that too,
but none of the addresses

08:18.430 --> 08:19.900
came anywhere close to mine.

08:21.500 --> 08:23.499
Look, all I know is that
the Bensons are clearly

08:23.500 --> 08:26.899
going through something.
The question is, what?

08:26.900 --> 08:30.609
Actually, I think I know.

08:30.610 --> 08:32.409
Andrea was their ten-year-old daughter.

08:32.409 --> 08:35.549
She, uh, died three years ago.

08:35.549 --> 08:40.820
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:44.220 --> 08:45.860
So, uh, any ideas

08:45.880 --> 08:47.720
on how we go about helping the Bensons?

08:47.740 --> 08:49.250
[SIGHS]

08:49.260 --> 08:52.559
I don't know.

08:52.560 --> 08:54.299
I mean, after my mom passed,

08:54.300 --> 08:56.669
there wasn't much anyone could
do to help me through it.

08:56.670 --> 08:58.770
You know, I had to get
there on my own time,

08:58.780 --> 09:00.140
and it's different for everyone.

09:00.190 --> 09:01.619
Well, maybe that's why the God Account

09:01.620 --> 09:03.019
thinks you can help them.

09:03.020 --> 09:04.319
You know what they're going through.

09:04.320 --> 09:06.289
But I know what loss is,

09:06.290 --> 09:08.359
but not what they're experiencing.

09:08.360 --> 09:10.659
If we charge into their
lives without a plan,

09:10.660 --> 09:12.300
we can make things worse.

09:12.320 --> 09:14.850
So where do we start?

09:14.880 --> 09:17.099
Well, what about Jen Levy?

09:17.100 --> 09:18.739
Well, like I said, we've already tried,

09:18.740 --> 09:20.269
and we couldn't find her.

09:20.270 --> 09:22.080
Actually, we haven't tried everything.

09:22.120 --> 09:24.909
I mean, either the God Account
hacked the shipping company

09:24.910 --> 09:26.949
or it was an error.

09:26.950 --> 09:29.149
I could just take the
package, go to IdentitySeal,

09:29.150 --> 09:31.489
scan the barcode and
see what I find out.

09:31.490 --> 09:33.389
All right, call us if you find anything.

09:33.390 --> 09:35.160
- All right.
- Yeah.

09:36.160 --> 09:39.589
We have to go meet John Dove.

09:39.590 --> 09:40.929
It's really good to see you guys.

09:40.930 --> 09:43.559
I admit I was surprised
to hear from you.

09:43.560 --> 09:44.959
Yeah, yeah, it's been a while.

09:44.960 --> 09:46.869
We figured it'd be nice to catch up.

09:46.870 --> 09:48.739
Well, things have
definitely turned around

09:48.740 --> 09:50.869
since the last time we saw each other.

09:50.870 --> 09:52.640
I'm practicing medicine again.

09:52.700 --> 09:54.669
I even got back together
with my girlfriend.

09:54.670 --> 09:56.320
That's great.

09:56.340 --> 09:58.249
The reason why we wanted to meet

09:58.250 --> 10:00.499
is because we are trying
to get some information

10:00.500 --> 10:03.119
about a former patient of yours.

10:03.120 --> 10:04.889
Simon Hayes.

10:04.890 --> 10:06.519
You did a bone marrow transplant

10:06.520 --> 10:07.689
for him five years ago.

10:07.690 --> 10:09.440
I'm sorry, I just can't speak to that.

10:09.450 --> 10:12.659
The doctor-patient
confidentiality and all.

10:12.660 --> 10:14.490
But why... why do you ask?

10:16.280 --> 10:18.399
Okay, this is gonna sound crazy

10:18.400 --> 10:20.669
because usually it does,

10:20.670 --> 10:24.690
but a few months ago I
was friended by someone

10:24.700 --> 10:27.470
claiming to be God on Facebook.

10:28.640 --> 10:30.760
And what did they want?

10:30.770 --> 10:32.250
They started sending
me Friend Suggestions

10:32.260 --> 10:33.500
of people in need of help.

10:33.540 --> 10:35.720
So we help them.

10:35.780 --> 10:37.949
- Help them how?
- By finding things

10:37.950 --> 10:40.039
they can't see, like hidden connections

10:40.040 --> 10:43.619
between strangers or
reconnecting family.

10:43.620 --> 10:46.540
Even saving someone's life.

10:46.550 --> 10:49.459
<i>[SOFT MUSIC]</i>

10:49.460 --> 10:51.059
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:51.060 --> 10:53.670
[CHUCKLES] That... that was the reason

10:53.680 --> 10:55.300
you followed me onto
the subway that day?

10:55.330 --> 10:57.439
Yeah.

10:57.440 --> 10:59.660
You were my first Friend Suggestion.

11:01.900 --> 11:04.519
We're trying to find out
who's behind the account,

11:04.520 --> 11:07.880
and we think it could be Simon Hayes.

11:09.520 --> 11:11.949
Look, the Hippocratic Oath forbids me

11:11.950 --> 11:14.699
from talking about my patients.

11:14.700 --> 11:20.059
However, Simon wasn't
technically my patient.

11:20.060 --> 11:23.000
He wasn't the recipient of
the bone marrow transplant.

11:23.010 --> 11:25.019
He was the donor.

11:25.020 --> 11:26.279
Yes.

11:26.280 --> 11:27.980
[CELL PHONE CHIMES]

11:30.100 --> 11:32.489
I have to go back to the hospital.

11:32.490 --> 11:34.619
[SIGHS]

11:34.620 --> 11:36.459
It was good to see you guys again,

11:36.460 --> 11:39.799
and, look, if you do find out
who's behind this God Account,

11:39.800 --> 11:41.999
you let me know. I owe them a thank you.

11:42.000 --> 11:43.280
Yeah.

11:43.300 --> 11:45.140
- Thank you.
- Bye.

11:47.560 --> 11:50.009
If Simon Hayes was the donor,
who was the recipient?

11:50.010 --> 11:52.739
I don't know.

11:52.740 --> 11:55.049
But maybe they're connected
to the God Account somehow.

11:55.050 --> 11:57.409
<i>[COMPELLING MUSIC]</i>

11:57.410 --> 11:58.960
[CELL PHONE BUZZING]

11:59.890 --> 12:02.439
_

12:02.440 --> 12:03.850
Hm.

12:03.860 --> 12:05.900
_

12:05.940 --> 12:07.800
_

12:10.600 --> 12:12.860
_

12:13.840 --> 12:15.880
- [SIGHS]
- Everything all right, man?

12:16.600 --> 12:18.899
Uh, yeah.

12:18.900 --> 12:20.300
Who's Jen Levy?

12:21.040 --> 12:23.680
I have no idea. Why do you ask?

12:23.700 --> 12:25.449
Oh, you have a rather large package

12:25.450 --> 12:27.120
of hers on your table here.

12:27.180 --> 12:29.260
[CHUCKLES AWKWARDLY] Uh,

12:29.270 --> 12:31.579
I'm just... I'm holding
on to it for a friend,

12:31.580 --> 12:33.719
Miles Finer. He, uh...

12:33.720 --> 12:35.120
He got it by mistake.

12:35.140 --> 12:38.519
That's, like, super weird, right?

12:38.520 --> 12:39.740
Not really.

12:39.750 --> 12:42.229
I mean, you know, people get
sent the wrong packages

12:42.230 --> 12:43.429
quite a bit.

12:43.430 --> 12:45.859
Yeah, I'll have to let Miles know.

12:45.860 --> 12:49.400
You know, he works here.

12:49.440 --> 12:51.999
Oh, yeah, sounds familiar. Miles Finer.

12:52.000 --> 12:53.469
Customer Service, right?

12:53.470 --> 12:55.969
Wait, how'd you know I meant Miles Finer

12:55.970 --> 12:57.640
when I never told you his last name?

12:57.660 --> 13:00.139
Because you told me his last name.

13:00.140 --> 13:01.909
About ten seconds ago.

13:01.910 --> 13:03.740
- Oh. Right.
- Hm. Mm-hmm.

13:06.000 --> 13:08.789
Anyway, uh, what did you
want to see me about?

13:08.790 --> 13:12.559
Right, so the Palo Alto
team arrives in one week,

13:12.560 --> 13:15.319
and before they get here, I
want to transform this room

13:15.320 --> 13:17.399
into a high-tech hub.

13:17.400 --> 13:19.099
I want the team on a secure server,

13:19.100 --> 13:20.859
the works. Can you do that?

13:20.860 --> 13:22.400
- Yeah, uh...
- Perfect.

13:22.410 --> 13:24.039
I'll head down to IT right now

13:24.040 --> 13:25.460
and let them know what we need.

13:25.470 --> 13:27.080
Great. Go to it.

13:28.280 --> 13:30.040
- All right.
- Okay.

13:30.050 --> 13:33.739
<i>[MYSTERIOUS MUSIC]</i>

13:33.740 --> 13:36.949
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:36.950 --> 13:38.479
[DOOR OPENS]

13:38.480 --> 13:39.860
Interview's tomorrow.

13:40.480 --> 13:42.920
Do I need to line up another
journalist to take it?

13:48.520 --> 13:50.089
No.

13:50.090 --> 13:52.759
I knew I could count on you.

13:52.760 --> 13:55.320
Actually, I have one condition.

13:56.330 --> 13:58.000
I'm listening.

13:59.320 --> 14:03.539
You built this company
on solid reporting,

14:03.540 --> 14:05.709
which means facts matter.

14:05.710 --> 14:07.609
Now, if I'm gonna do this article,

14:07.610 --> 14:10.349
put my reputation on the
line, I need to put certain.

14:10.350 --> 14:11.819
So here's my offer.

14:11.820 --> 14:13.120
I take the interview with Simon,

14:13.140 --> 14:15.080
but if I walk away
thinking he's not behind

14:15.100 --> 14:17.989
the God Account, we kill the story.

14:17.990 --> 14:19.140
Deal?

14:21.860 --> 14:25.500
This guy, Miles, must really
mean something to you.

14:27.400 --> 14:29.220
Yeah, he does.

14:29.240 --> 14:31.769
Fine.

14:31.770 --> 14:34.869
But if Simon Hayes is
behind the God Account,

14:34.870 --> 14:36.460
you're writing the story.

14:41.040 --> 14:44.349
Stay tuned for more of
the Millennial Prophet

14:44.350 --> 14:47.219
right here on FreeVerse.

14:47.220 --> 14:49.080
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

14:51.580 --> 14:53.259
Mr. Benson, what are you doing here?

14:53.260 --> 14:55.259
I'm sorry for showing up like this.

14:55.260 --> 14:57.059
My wife explained what happened...

14:57.060 --> 14:59.099
that we sent the package
to you by mistake.

14:59.100 --> 15:00.840
I got your address from
the shipping company,

15:00.850 --> 15:03.199
and well I apologize for how I reacted.

15:03.200 --> 15:04.869
It's no problem. Come on in.

15:04.870 --> 15:05.880
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

15:08.200 --> 15:10.999
I don't mean to take up your time,

15:11.000 --> 15:15.749
um, it's just my wife and
I have changed our minds.

15:15.750 --> 15:18.209
- We'd like the package back.
- I understand.

15:18.210 --> 15:20.750
Yeah, my friend has been
trying to track down

15:20.780 --> 15:22.940
the buyer, so he has it,
but I can give him a call

15:22.950 --> 15:24.160
and have him come by.

15:26.880 --> 15:28.519
Hey. Hey, Rakesh.

15:28.520 --> 15:30.429
I'm here with Mr. Benson.

15:30.430 --> 15:33.040
He was hoping to get his package back.

15:33.050 --> 15:35.869
<i>Do you mind coming by my
place and dropping it off?</i>

15:35.870 --> 15:38.469
Uh, Miles, that's gonna be a problem.

15:38.470 --> 15:42.060
<i>[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC]</i>

15:42.070 --> 15:43.580
<i>The package is gone.</i>

15:46.660 --> 15:48.469
<i>My friend thinks someone in the mailroom</i>

15:48.470 --> 15:49.979
may have taken the package by mistake,

15:49.980 --> 15:52.959
but don't worry, okay? We will find it.

15:52.960 --> 15:54.329
Thank you.

15:54.330 --> 15:57.839
Excuse me. Do you mind if I ask...

15:57.840 --> 15:59.810
What was in the package?

16:01.320 --> 16:03.020
My daughter's violin.

16:04.960 --> 16:07.620
She passed away.

16:07.770 --> 16:10.139
Three years ago tomorrow, actually.

16:10.140 --> 16:12.540
[EXHALES SLOWLY] I'm sorry.

16:13.740 --> 16:18.120
Doctor said it was a brain aneurysm.

16:18.600 --> 16:20.649
We were there when it happened.

16:20.650 --> 16:22.089
[SNIFFLES]

16:22.090 --> 16:27.080
One minute she was playing
in the snow and the next...

16:27.980 --> 16:31.360
Karen and I are rushing
her to the hospital.

16:33.420 --> 16:36.660
Even after all this time,
it doesn't feel real.

16:36.670 --> 16:38.740
Have you two talked to someone?

16:38.790 --> 16:40.919
Yeah, but these past three years

16:40.920 --> 16:43.420
Karen and I have become,
like, strangers.

16:44.780 --> 16:49.259
And I don't know how to fix it.

16:49.260 --> 16:52.599
I don't know how to
help her move forward.

16:52.600 --> 16:55.100
Which is why you sold the violin.

16:56.740 --> 16:59.240
My daughter loved music.

17:00.560 --> 17:04.319
That violin brought her so much joy,

17:04.339 --> 17:06.400
so much life.

17:07.619 --> 17:09.839
She would have wanted it to be played,

17:09.849 --> 17:14.119
not just sitting in a
box, collecting dust.

17:14.180 --> 17:18.559
I thought that passing it on would...

17:18.560 --> 17:21.760
I don't know, honor her memory.

17:23.440 --> 17:26.628
And allow us to finally take
that first step forward.

17:26.630 --> 17:28.636
I thought Karen would understand that

17:28.637 --> 17:29.770
more than anyone.

17:29.780 --> 17:31.070
What do you mean?

17:31.120 --> 17:33.280
She's a violin teacher,

17:34.010 --> 17:37.020
and they had a really special bond.

17:37.040 --> 17:38.640
I found Jen Levy online,

17:38.660 --> 17:40.440
and she needed a violin.

17:40.450 --> 17:41.679
But she couldn't afford one.

17:41.680 --> 17:45.800
I told Karen I thought it was a sign.

17:46.600 --> 17:49.689
Then when the violin found
its way back to us.

17:49.690 --> 17:53.640
She saw it as one that you
were supposed to keep it.

17:56.000 --> 17:58.069
Yeah.

17:58.070 --> 18:00.399
Anyhow...

18:00.400 --> 18:02.499
I should get going. You
call me when you find it?

18:02.500 --> 18:03.869
Yeah.

18:03.870 --> 18:06.869
<i>[SOLEMN MUSIC]</i>

18:06.870 --> 18:10.009
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:10.010 --> 18:12.580
Can I ask you something?

18:14.120 --> 18:16.079
Do you really think
getting the violin back

18:16.080 --> 18:17.180
will help your wife?

18:18.020 --> 18:19.200
No.

18:22.400 --> 18:25.729
But it's what she needs right now.

18:25.730 --> 18:28.160
It's something I can't give her.

18:35.400 --> 18:39.010
<i>Miss Bloom, nice to meet you.</i>

18:39.040 --> 18:41.820
Shall we, uh, have a seat?

18:46.840 --> 18:48.920
[CLEARS THROAT]

18:51.120 --> 18:52.889
[RECORDER BEEPS]

18:52.890 --> 18:55.480
- Do you mind?
- No, no. Not at all.

18:55.520 --> 18:56.739
You know, I've been looking forward

18:56.740 --> 18:58.260
to sitting down with you.

18:58.960 --> 19:00.389
- Really?
- Yeah.

19:00.390 --> 19:02.200
I read a bunch of your articles,

19:02.220 --> 19:04.280
and, you know, they really spoke to me.

19:05.100 --> 19:06.999
- Thanks.
- I mean, this day and age,

19:07.000 --> 19:09.979
writing about people helping
one another and hope,

19:09.980 --> 19:13.239
you know, it's practically a
revolutionary act, you know?

19:13.240 --> 19:14.739
It did make me wonder

19:14.740 --> 19:17.139
why you'd want to speak with me?

19:17.140 --> 19:19.719
It just doesn't seem like
the CEO of a tech company

19:19.720 --> 19:22.420
is the type of everyman
you tend to profile.

19:22.460 --> 19:26.449
I guess I want to get to
know the man behind the CEO.

19:26.450 --> 19:28.389
For example, your time at Columbia,

19:28.390 --> 19:31.460
and what led you to start
Singular Dynamics.

19:31.520 --> 19:34.680
That's what you wanted
to talk to me about?

19:36.540 --> 19:39.469
Well, unless there's something else?

19:39.470 --> 19:41.799
Well, why don't we start with telling me

19:41.800 --> 19:42.840
why you're really here.

19:44.000 --> 19:45.540
[RECORDER BEEPS]

19:47.060 --> 19:48.809
Fine.

19:48.810 --> 19:50.300
I know you're working on something big.

19:50.320 --> 19:52.399
Like something that you've
gone to great lengths

19:52.400 --> 19:53.900
to keep secret.

19:53.980 --> 19:55.420
Uh-huh.

19:55.440 --> 19:58.119
A top secret project.
That's quite the scoop.

19:58.120 --> 20:00.519
Yeah, well, tell your boss

20:00.520 --> 20:02.320
he wasted a lot of favors, okay?

20:04.720 --> 20:06.560
Okay, your team from Palo Alto,

20:06.600 --> 20:10.199
the one that's been
working on this project,

20:10.200 --> 20:11.970
you're moving them to New York.

20:13.420 --> 20:14.859
Now, you wouldn't be doing this

20:14.860 --> 20:17.269
unless you were close to rolling it out,

20:17.270 --> 20:19.609
moving from trial phase to launch.

20:19.610 --> 20:21.120
That's why I'm here.

20:22.400 --> 20:24.849
Fewer than a dozen
people know about that,

20:24.850 --> 20:27.479
all of whom have signed NDAs, all right?

20:27.480 --> 20:29.300
It won't take me long
to find your source.

20:31.480 --> 20:33.549
I want to know what you're working on.

20:33.550 --> 20:35.960
Give me something or I'll
run with what I have.

20:35.980 --> 20:39.089
[SIGHS] Okay. Look.

20:39.090 --> 20:42.999
I've been working on
this a very long time.

20:43.000 --> 20:45.629
The trial phase went
live eight months ago,

20:45.630 --> 20:48.439
and the results were...
they were phenomenal.

20:48.440 --> 20:51.510
My code will change the
course of people's lives.

20:51.560 --> 20:54.709
Next week I host a gala,
and I'm going to announce.

20:54.710 --> 20:56.879
Hold off until after and
I'll give you an exclusive.

20:56.880 --> 21:00.640
I promise you it will be worth it.

21:00.660 --> 21:03.500
<i>[EDGY MUSIC]</i>

21:05.220 --> 21:08.919
Dude, Bryan, good to see ya.

21:08.920 --> 21:11.259
- It's Ryan.
- I know.

21:11.260 --> 21:14.189
Uh, so mailroom told me
you were doing rounds.

21:14.190 --> 21:16.059
Any chance you took a package?

21:16.060 --> 21:17.760
- No.
- From my... You sure?

21:17.770 --> 21:20.200
Yeah. What are you doing? Stop that.

21:20.280 --> 21:22.839
Dude, I just need that package, okay?

21:22.840 --> 21:24.200
If it was picked up,

21:24.210 --> 21:27.069
it's probably in the mailroom
for outgoing delivery.

21:27.070 --> 21:33.280
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:33.380 --> 21:38.180
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:39.420 --> 21:45.520
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:53.680 --> 21:56.139
So you're looking for a
clinical perspective

21:56.140 --> 21:58.109
on how to help Karen Benson move on?

21:58.110 --> 21:59.720
Do you have one?

22:00.370 --> 22:01.939
No.

22:01.940 --> 22:04.949
Because you can't, at least not
in the way you usually do.

22:04.950 --> 22:06.549
I mean, I get it.

22:06.550 --> 22:10.079
I never got over losing
Mom. You never forget.

22:10.080 --> 22:13.689
But at some point, I started
to reengage with the world,

22:13.690 --> 22:15.589
and I feel like Richard
is ready to do that

22:15.590 --> 22:17.260
but not Karen.

22:18.660 --> 22:21.599
People grieve differently, Miles.

22:21.600 --> 22:23.159
If she's not ready,

22:23.160 --> 22:25.129
pushing her will only make things worse.

22:25.130 --> 22:29.439
Richard doesn't think that his
marriage is going to last.

22:29.440 --> 22:31.480
I don't know how much
worse that can get.

22:32.640 --> 22:35.110
Unfortunately, most
couples don't survive

22:35.120 --> 22:36.240
the loss of a child.

22:36.250 --> 22:38.149
But the God Account thinks they can.

22:38.150 --> 22:41.009
I just have to figure out
how all the pieces connect.

22:41.010 --> 22:43.280
[CELL PHONE CHIMES]

22:43.920 --> 22:46.089
- _
- What's that?

22:46.090 --> 22:49.559
[LAUGHS] Just got a friend
request from Trish.

22:49.560 --> 22:51.180
She sent me one last week.

22:51.200 --> 22:52.899
You should check out that
photo of her and Dad

22:52.900 --> 22:54.480
at the church barbecue.

22:54.500 --> 22:56.329
What? What is it?

22:56.330 --> 23:00.460
Trish is friends with Karen Benson.

23:02.660 --> 23:03.960
[BELL RINGS]

23:03.980 --> 23:05.839
Hey, Trish.

23:05.840 --> 23:09.179
- Miles, what a nice surprise.
- Hey.

23:09.180 --> 23:11.780
I just got your friend request,
so I thought I would stop by

23:11.800 --> 23:13.710
and let you know that we are official.

23:13.720 --> 23:15.149
Oh, whoo-hoo and here I thought

23:15.150 --> 23:16.450
you were just ignoring you.

23:16.460 --> 23:17.799
What do you mean?

23:17.800 --> 23:19.689
I sent it that to you last week.

23:19.690 --> 23:21.460
I wonder why you just got it today.

23:21.520 --> 23:23.659
Oh, must be a glitch.

23:23.660 --> 23:26.220
Anyways, I was on your page

23:26.240 --> 23:29.099
and I noticed that you were
friends with Karen Benson.

23:29.100 --> 23:30.699
- Karen? Of course.
- Yeah.

23:30.700 --> 23:33.420
- Do you know her?
- Well, not until yesterday.

23:33.440 --> 23:34.980
She's my new Friend Suggestion.

23:35.000 --> 23:37.769
- Oh, I see.
- Yeah.

23:37.770 --> 23:39.719
You know they lost their daughter Andrea

23:39.720 --> 23:42.609
- a few years back.
- Yeah, yeah.

23:42.610 --> 23:44.379
Things are still pretty tough.

23:44.380 --> 23:47.249
I was wondering if you
could tell me about her.

23:47.250 --> 23:49.019
Karen's a music teacher.

23:49.020 --> 23:51.289
Came into the shop from time to time.

23:51.290 --> 23:53.359
We became Facebook friends,

23:53.360 --> 23:55.820
but we haven't spoken in a while.

23:55.880 --> 23:57.829
Oh.

23:57.830 --> 24:02.160
By chance, would you know
someone named Jen Levy?

24:02.180 --> 24:05.399
No. Sorry.

24:05.400 --> 24:07.099
Another Friend Suggestion?

24:07.100 --> 24:10.769
Not quite, but, uh...

24:10.770 --> 24:12.509
Anyways, I have to go.

24:12.510 --> 24:13.939
Oh, wait, Miles.

24:13.940 --> 24:16.660
I actually really wanted to
talk to you about something.

24:16.670 --> 24:19.439
I went to your dad's
walkabout yesterday,

24:19.440 --> 24:21.849
and I think he's having a hard time

24:21.850 --> 24:23.850
with what they're asking him to do.

24:23.900 --> 24:25.449
Wait, did he say something?

24:25.450 --> 24:28.389
No, but I... I could just tell.

24:28.390 --> 24:30.189
Do you think that you could talk to him?

24:30.190 --> 24:31.689
Yeah, yeah, I can,

24:31.690 --> 24:34.299
but if you're really concerned

24:34.300 --> 24:36.660
I think it would be
better coming from you.

24:36.680 --> 24:38.280
- [FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]
- Yeah.

24:38.300 --> 24:40.869
- Hi, can I help you?
- Yes.

24:40.870 --> 24:43.119
I'm looking for a nice violin,

24:43.120 --> 24:45.169
but I don't have much to spend.

24:45.170 --> 24:49.339
Unfortunately, we don't
have any right now.

24:49.340 --> 24:51.610
I can't believe this.

24:54.160 --> 24:57.160
I bought this amazing violin
on Facebook Marketplace,

24:57.180 --> 24:58.919
but it never arrived.

24:58.920 --> 25:01.259
I reached out to the
seller, but unfortunately

25:01.260 --> 25:05.329
- I haven't heard back.
- I... I'm so sorry.

25:05.330 --> 25:08.430
But you wouldn't so
happen to be Jen Levy?

25:08.500 --> 25:11.780
Yeah. How do you know that?

25:17.190 --> 25:19.519
So you're telling me
that the violin I bought

25:19.520 --> 25:21.280
from the Bensons ended up at your house.

25:21.310 --> 25:22.780
- Yeah.
- How's that possible?

25:22.800 --> 25:24.019
I have no idea.

25:24.020 --> 25:26.480
Someone must have messed
up on the shipping label.

25:26.500 --> 25:29.780
And then I meet you here.
That's a crazy coincidence.

25:29.830 --> 25:31.529
Well, the world's full of them.

25:31.530 --> 25:32.699
But this is great.

25:32.700 --> 25:33.940
Can we go to your house and pick it up?

25:33.960 --> 25:36.270
Actually, I kind of lost it.

25:36.320 --> 25:38.819
It's a long story, but
I promised the Bensons

25:38.820 --> 25:41.319
if I found it, I would
return it to them.

25:41.320 --> 25:44.089
They changed their minds
about selling it.

25:44.090 --> 25:45.960
I'm sorry.

25:46.780 --> 25:49.860
I knew this was too good to be true.

25:49.940 --> 25:52.020
She's gonna be so disappointed.

25:52.600 --> 25:54.059
Who?

25:54.060 --> 25:55.499
My daughter, Lindsay.

25:55.500 --> 25:59.209
She's 13, and tonight's
kind of a special occasion.

25:59.210 --> 26:01.549
It's her first recital.

26:01.550 --> 26:03.549
She's been playing an
old beat-up instrument,

26:03.550 --> 26:05.719
so I wanted to do something
special for her.

26:05.720 --> 26:08.849
And that's when I saw the
Holstein violin on Facebook,

26:08.850 --> 26:12.359
and the Bensons agreed to
sell it for next to nothing.

26:12.360 --> 26:14.059
I know it sounds silly,

26:14.060 --> 26:17.430
but finding them felt
like it was meant to be.

26:17.480 --> 26:19.929
Look, I... I can't make any promises,

26:19.930 --> 26:22.769
but if the violin turns up,

26:22.770 --> 26:25.140
I'll talk to the Bensons
and see what I can do.

26:26.640 --> 26:28.100
Thank you.

26:31.240 --> 26:33.179
So you think the God
Account wants us to get

26:33.180 --> 26:34.639
Mrs. Benson to see Lindsay play.

26:34.640 --> 26:37.209
Maybe seeing Lindsay
with Andrea's violin

26:37.210 --> 26:39.219
and hearing it played
again is what she needs

26:39.220 --> 26:40.979
to finally take that step forward.

26:40.980 --> 26:42.989
Yeah, it makes sense.

26:42.990 --> 26:45.159
It's just one problem.

26:45.160 --> 26:46.959
We don't have the violin.

26:46.960 --> 26:49.290
- Mm-hmm.
- I'll text Rakesh.

26:49.300 --> 26:51.189
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

26:51.190 --> 26:53.600
Miles? Open up.

26:56.120 --> 26:57.620
- Hey, what's up?
- Hey.

26:57.630 --> 27:00.099
So I found it.

27:00.100 --> 27:02.109
- You did? That's great.
- Mm-hmm.

27:02.110 --> 27:03.160
Where is it?

27:03.170 --> 27:05.100
Well, someone in the mailroom

27:05.110 --> 27:07.040
grabbed it off of my desk by mistake

27:07.060 --> 27:08.399
and had it sent out by courier,

27:08.400 --> 27:09.920
but that's a good thing

27:09.930 --> 27:12.949
'cause the company we use
is a very reliable one.

27:12.950 --> 27:15.389
So I've been tracking
them on my phone, and...

27:15.390 --> 27:20.119
they should be here in three, two, one.

27:20.120 --> 27:21.620
[KNOCKING AT DOOR]

27:22.130 --> 27:23.440
[LAUGHS]

27:24.460 --> 27:26.560
[LAUGHS] Nice.

27:27.580 --> 27:29.460
So how's work, Cara?

27:30.330 --> 27:32.839
Huh? Fine. Why?

27:32.840 --> 27:34.419
You really think you can
interview Simon Hayes

27:34.420 --> 27:36.920
in IdentitySeal and one
of us wouldn't see you?

27:37.870 --> 27:39.660
Okay, look, my boss arranged it.

27:39.670 --> 27:40.879
I had no choice.

27:40.880 --> 27:42.749
You and Miles had a deal
that you wouldn't write

27:42.750 --> 27:44.160
about the God Account,

27:44.170 --> 27:46.260
and if that's changed,
you need to tell him.

27:47.280 --> 27:49.749
[STRAINING] All right.

27:49.750 --> 27:51.019
- Got it.
- Great.

27:51.020 --> 27:52.619
Now we just need to convince

27:52.620 --> 27:54.180
Karen to see Lindsay play.

27:54.200 --> 27:56.289
That is not gonna be easy.

27:56.290 --> 28:00.530
No, but I have an idea of
how we can get her there.

28:00.560 --> 28:02.499
<i>Arthur, hi. Do you have a minute?</i>

28:02.500 --> 28:05.199
Of course. We didn't
get a chance to talk

28:05.200 --> 28:06.999
after the walkabout yesterday.

28:07.000 --> 28:08.920
Well, you were in a deep
conversation with Diana.

28:08.930 --> 28:10.180
I didn't really want to interrupt.

28:10.200 --> 28:12.769
Well... ?

28:12.770 --> 28:14.220
What did you think?

28:14.240 --> 28:17.180
The parishioners loved you.

28:19.480 --> 28:21.449
But... ?

28:21.450 --> 28:27.019
<i>[SOFT MUSIC]</i>

28:27.020 --> 28:29.689
When the board suggested that you play

28:29.690 --> 28:31.689
the political game to win the election,

28:31.690 --> 28:34.359
I saw their point, and I even pushed you

28:34.360 --> 28:37.430
to talk to Miles and Ali
when you were having doubts.

28:38.320 --> 28:40.080
But I think I was wrong.

28:40.970 --> 28:43.369
You don't want to
become bishop this way,

28:43.370 --> 28:45.639
pretending to be someone you're not.

28:45.640 --> 28:48.470
No, I want to become bishop
to be the person that I am

28:48.480 --> 28:50.460
to make change for the better,

28:50.470 --> 28:53.160
and to ensure that the
church takes a step forward

28:53.180 --> 28:55.279
- and not backward.
- Then show them that now.

28:55.280 --> 28:57.419
- Not later.
- I will.

28:57.420 --> 29:00.560
- But when the time is right.
- The time is right.

29:01.800 --> 29:05.359
If you don't win as the real you,

29:05.360 --> 29:07.900
I'm afraid you'll regret
how you got there.

29:11.000 --> 29:13.560
I found Andrea's violin.

29:13.570 --> 29:16.739
Thank God. Where is it?

29:16.740 --> 29:19.780
I gave it back to the
person you sold it to.

29:20.610 --> 29:22.140
Why would you do that?

29:22.150 --> 29:24.519
Because her daughter is a violinist

29:24.520 --> 29:26.460
and she has a recital tonight.

29:26.470 --> 29:29.819
Look, I cannot imagine what
you are going through.

29:29.820 --> 29:33.289
No, you can't.

29:33.290 --> 29:36.919
We didn't just lose Andrea.
We lost our future.

29:36.920 --> 29:40.529
Watching Andrea grow up,
fall in love, get married,

29:40.530 --> 29:42.729
play Carnegie Hall... we lost all of it.

29:42.730 --> 29:46.369
Three years ago today and it
still feels like yesterday.

29:46.370 --> 29:48.769
- Karen...
- No.

29:48.770 --> 29:51.369
I know you're ready to
move forward, but I'm not.

29:51.370 --> 29:54.509
Because I don't know how to do that.

29:54.510 --> 29:57.820
I don't know who I'm supposed to be.

29:59.980 --> 30:02.649
All I know is that I'm trying
to hold on to her memory

30:02.650 --> 30:04.750
as best I can.

30:04.820 --> 30:07.819
And if I get rid of the one
thing that she loved the most,

30:07.820 --> 30:10.040
I'll have nothing left
to remember her by.

30:10.050 --> 30:12.589
Letting go of Andrea's
violin does not mean

30:12.590 --> 30:14.300
that you're letting go of her.

30:15.230 --> 30:17.159
Miles is right.

30:17.160 --> 30:18.999
Her violin can keep making music,

30:19.000 --> 30:21.099
keep making people happy.

30:21.100 --> 30:23.570
It's what Andrea would want.

30:24.780 --> 30:26.909
Please.

30:26.910 --> 30:29.979
All I'm asking you to do
is come to the recital.

30:29.980 --> 30:32.179
If you want the violin back after that,

30:32.180 --> 30:33.380
it's yours.

30:33.400 --> 30:37.450
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

30:37.500 --> 30:40.219
<i>[APPLAUSE]</i>

30:40.220 --> 30:42.100
Our last performer of the evening,

30:42.110 --> 30:45.089
playing the violin, Lindsay Levy.

30:45.090 --> 30:47.929
Looks like they saved the best for last.

30:47.930 --> 30:49.799
I know you'll do that violin proud.

30:49.800 --> 30:51.260
Thanks.

30:52.700 --> 30:55.200
- See you after the show.
- Yeah.

31:01.240 --> 31:04.380
- Any sign of the Bensons?
- No.

31:06.760 --> 31:10.879
[PLAYS MELANCHOLY MELODY]

31:10.880 --> 31:17.150
♪ ♪

31:17.160 --> 31:18.840
[DOOR OPENS]

31:18.930 --> 31:26.960
♪ ♪

31:27.240 --> 31:34.000
♪ ♪

31:35.300 --> 31:42.880
♪ ♪

31:50.460 --> 31:52.390
Hey.

31:52.410 --> 31:53.660
Hey.

31:53.720 --> 31:56.820
Where's Karen?

31:56.880 --> 31:59.999
She's not coming.

32:00.000 --> 32:02.420
She just couldn't do it.

32:03.400 --> 32:05.140
Why did you?

32:05.180 --> 32:07.669
I wanted to hear my daughter's violin

32:07.670 --> 32:08.810
played one more time.

32:11.860 --> 32:15.949
But when I close my eyes, it's like

32:15.950 --> 32:18.180
Andrea's playing.

32:19.700 --> 32:22.220
Like she's here. [CRYING SOFTLY]

32:22.320 --> 32:25.729
I remember her first recital.

32:25.730 --> 32:28.929
Karen was so nervous.

32:28.930 --> 32:31.659
The moment she started to play,

32:31.660 --> 32:35.000
she grabbed my hand so tight.

32:36.080 --> 32:38.560
I thought she'd never let go.

32:41.200 --> 32:44.480
It's been a long time since
we had a moment like that.

32:45.740 --> 32:48.779
I thought if she came tonight,

32:48.780 --> 32:51.080
she might remember that.

32:53.320 --> 32:55.600
But I couldn't get through to her.

32:57.320 --> 33:00.400
I don't think I ever will.

33:02.520 --> 33:06.420
- Thanks for trying.
- [SOFTLY] Yeah.

33:13.420 --> 33:15.319
[SIGHS] I'm sorry, Miles.

33:15.320 --> 33:17.160
I really thought we had it figured out.

33:17.200 --> 33:19.150
All the pieces were
set to come together.

33:19.160 --> 33:20.240
Yeah, I guess we were wrong.

33:20.250 --> 33:22.529
Maybe for the first time we just

33:22.530 --> 33:24.180
can't help our Friend Suggestion.

33:24.190 --> 33:26.129
I hate to say it, but I think

33:26.130 --> 33:28.199
maybe the one thing Mrs.
Benson needs is the one thing

33:28.200 --> 33:30.720
you can't give her... her daughter back.

33:30.740 --> 33:32.139
Yeah, but it doesn't make any sense.

33:32.140 --> 33:33.480
Why would the God Account go through

33:33.500 --> 33:35.869
all this trouble sending us the Bensons,

33:35.870 --> 33:39.440
Andrea's violin, Jen Levy.

33:41.900 --> 33:43.809
Is that John Dove?

33:43.810 --> 33:45.260
Hm?

33:45.950 --> 33:50.170
Wait, how does John Dove know Jen Levy?

33:50.180 --> 33:52.350
We're about to find out.

33:54.180 --> 33:56.159
You're a real talent.

33:56.160 --> 33:58.329
John.

33:58.330 --> 34:01.559
Miles, Cara, what are
you guys doing here?

34:01.560 --> 34:06.469
Uh, Jen and I, uh, are new friends,

34:06.470 --> 34:08.639
and we came to hear Lindsay play.

34:08.639 --> 34:09.879
How do you all know each other?

34:09.880 --> 34:12.009
John is Lindsay's doctor.

34:12.010 --> 34:13.579
He saved her life.

34:13.580 --> 34:16.208
In fact, that was three years ago today.

34:16.210 --> 34:18.909
<i>[SOFT MUSIC]</i>

34:18.909 --> 34:20.549
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:20.550 --> 34:21.849
Miles.

34:21.850 --> 34:24.620
What's going on?

34:24.639 --> 34:26.060
[GASPS]

34:27.389 --> 34:29.530
Andrea's violin.

34:31.000 --> 34:33.649
Thank you for keeping your
word and returning it.

34:33.650 --> 34:36.760
Well, actually we brought
something more than that.

34:37.980 --> 34:39.260
Your husband told me that

34:39.270 --> 34:40.560
when he closed his eyes tonight,

34:40.570 --> 34:42.020
he could hear Andrea playing.

34:42.570 --> 34:44.539
And he was right.

34:44.540 --> 34:46.079
What are you talking about?

34:46.080 --> 34:48.060
Well, three years ago
Lindsay was suffering

34:48.070 --> 34:50.379
from congenital heart failure.

34:50.380 --> 34:52.719
Without a transplant,
she wasn't gonna live.

34:52.719 --> 34:56.219
Andrea's heart saved her life.

35:03.600 --> 35:07.500
The last thing we decided to
do was donate her organs.

35:07.540 --> 35:10.660
We never knew where they went.

35:12.180 --> 35:15.540
I heard your daughter was
an amazing violinist.

35:17.540 --> 35:19.779
- She was.
- When I was sick,

35:19.780 --> 35:21.180
I made a list of things

35:21.200 --> 35:23.660
I'd promise myself I'd do if I lived.

35:23.700 --> 35:26.419
One of them was learn how
to play an instrument.

35:26.420 --> 35:30.849
So my mom took me to a
secondhand music shop,

35:30.850 --> 35:34.320
and for some reason, the
violin spoke to me.

35:35.880 --> 35:37.480
Now I know why.

35:40.040 --> 35:41.920
I think she'd want you to have this.

